{"id":"1109.6480","submitter":"Mikhail Krivoruchenko","authors":"M. I. Krivoruchenko","title":"Semiclassical methods of deformation quantisation in transport theory","comments":"26 pages, PDF. To appear in: Quantum Mechanics, Vol. 3, Ed. M. R.\n  Pahlavani (InTech - Open Access Publisher, Zagreb, 2012)","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.5772/2540","report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We provide an introduction to deformation quantisation and discuss the\napplication of the formalism in solving the evolution problem for many-body\nsystems in terms of semiclassical expansion. In any fixed order of expansion\nover the Planck's constant, the evolution problem can be reduced to a\nstatistical-mechanics problem of calculating an ensemble of quantum\ncharacteristics in the phase space and their Jacobi fields. In comparison with\nthe corresponding rules of classical statistical mechanics, the rules for\ncomputing the probabilities and time-dependent averages of observables are\nmodified. The evolution equations represent a finite system of first-order\nordinary differential equations for quantum trajectories in the phase space and\nthe associated Jacobi fields. Quantum characteristics allow for the consistent\ninclusion of specific quantum effects, such as non-localities and coherence, in\nthe description of the propagation of particles in the transport models. Since\nthe late 1980s - early 1990s, when the first transport models were created for\nmodeling heavy-ion collisions, computing power has increased by about five\norders of magnitude. This dramatic rise in computing power makes it possible to\ninclude Jacobi fields in the collision dynamics, to extend beyond the classical\ntreatment of phase-space trajectories, currently adopted in all of the\ntransport models.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 29 Sep 2011 11:19:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-07-03"}
